    <title>Combined summary - Capital Efficient Honeypots w/ "Scorched Earth" Doublespending Protection</title>
    <updated>2023-06-11T19:55:24.887995+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2016-August/013072.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin-based honeypots are a proposed solution for detecting cyber attacks and incentivizing attackers to reveal information about their intrusion. The honeypot secret key is shared among all N servers, while each server has a unique signature with SIGHASH_SINGLE, paying a token amount to a notification address created with a discriminator secret key. A pre-signed standard transaction can be used instead, spending the honeypot txout to two addresses, a per-server canary address, and a change address. However, there are potential disadvantages to using non-standard SIGHASH flags, such as flagging by risk analysis at exchanges and the like, which could threaten the fungibility of the reward. To improve on this concept, a "scorched earth" version of the honeypot pre-signed transaction would also be provided. A smart contract incentivizing publication of a hacked server was also discussed, but owners can still redeem coins at any time.A discussion on the bitcoin-dev mailing list involved using multiple servers to secure Bitcoin transactions. One suggestion was to use a single 1-of-m multisig transaction with one key on each server. Covert tripwires were suggested as a better solution, but in cases where shared tripwires allow for significantly more funds to be available, it could be a worthwhile trade-off. The value of an intruder's activity compared to the value of coins would determine whether they would attempt to bypass covert or shared tripwires. Standardizing the location of tripwires was proposed to make it easier for intruders to find funds, with "/var/honeypot" as a possible Standardâ„¢ location.The proposal under discussion is not quite a traditional honeypot since it offers a reward to attackers, making it okay for them to know they've been detected. There is no way to prevent the owner from redeeming the coins at any time. The value of their activity compared to the value of the coins would determine whether they would attempt to bypass covert or shared tripwires.Jimmy asked Peter Todd if his idea of a Bitcoin honeypot was related to the Bitcoin Vigil program published in 2014. Todd clarified that the idea of a Bitcoin honeypot was not originally his and was likely related to the Bitcoin Vigil program. He expressed interest in giving credit to anyone who had previously invented the techniques he and Jeff Coleman used for the Bitcoin honeypot. In summary, honeypots and tripwires can be effective tools for detecting cyber attacks and incentivizing attackers to reveal information about their intrusion. However, there are potential disadvantages and trade-offs to consider when implementing these systems. The use of tripwires may be ineffective if an attacker plans to use the compromised server as a foothold for further attacks. The location of tripwires could be standardized to make it easier for intruders to find funds. Finally, the analogy to wildlife animal research was offered, where bait is used to attract targets and discover their existence, even when there is no intention of harming the animal.</summary>
